2026-04-21 01:31:53 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['battery_or_wall_wart_source', 'power_supply_module_polarity_configuration'] hypothesis_explanation='The multimeter reading shows the supposed battery/wall-wart positive terminal at −12 V relative to the system reference and the negative at 0 V. This means the external source is wired or labeled with reversed polarity with respect to the power supply module’s internal definition of + and −. The green power-supply LED (wired to turn on only when the module sees correct polarity) is off, which is consistent with this inversion. \n\nAt the same time, the inter-module cables are connected consistently “+ to +” and “− to −” from the PSU through the control module to the load. Therefore, from the load’s perspective it is also seeing reversed polarity (its diode blocks current), so the main lamp cannot turn on. The control-module red LED is designed to turn on when the 12 V line from the PSU is mistakenly connected to the 0 V line; with the source reversed and the cabling kept nominal, the internal reference in the control module now sees the higher potential where it expects 0 V, so the indicator lights, flagging the polarity problem.\n\nThus, the root cause is not a failed component but a polarity/configuration fault: the external 12 V source (battery pack or wall wart) is connected with its positive and negative reversed relative to the power-supply module’s intended polarity, and that incorrect polarity is being propagated unchanged through the correctly wired modules. Correcting the source polarity (or reconfiguring the module’s jack wiring to match the actual source polarity) should restore normal operation, turning off the red LED, turning on the green LED, and allowing the load lamp to operate when the switch is closed.'
